2025-06-27

The guideSeq (Genome-wide Unbiased Identification of Double-strand breaks Enabled by Sequencing) method enables comprehensive detection and quantification of off-target activity by capturing double-strand breaks across the genome through oligonucleotide tagging, followed by sequencing and bioinformatic analysis.

This report presents different tables and graphical representations to help in the interpretation of GuideSeq experiments.

Working directory : /media/Data/common/guideseq_gnt_dev2/test

Pipeline version: To Be Extracted from pipeline file name when release (2025/01/16)

The analysis was performed with bulge tolerance.

All parameters can be found in Configuration settings at the end of this document.

Best match found

Table 2 contains information about the best match(es) for each library.

Best matches are clusters with the minimal number of edits in the gRNA and PAM sequences ( not necessarily 0 ).

Table 2
library position cut offset Edits_gRNA Edits_PAM N_UMI_cluster Relative_abundance
VEGFA_s1_K562_neg 6:43769560 -1 0 0 2,093 14.59
VEGFA_s1_K562_pos 6:43769560 -2 0 0 591 10.33

  • position : theoretical cutting site based on gRNA alignment to gDNA and nuclease offset.

  • cut offset : Difference between theoretical cutting site and most frequent cutting site in the cluster.

  • Relative Abundance : Contribution of cluster abundance in % of total UMIs count. Only clusters with gRNA match with 6 edits and 0 UMIs are considered.

Reads alignment, cut sites calling and clustering

Table 4 contains a summary of the alignment step, calling step and clustering of cutting sites including :

  • The number of reads aligned on the genome

  • The number of UMIs detected (estimation of total number of cells)

  • The number of unique ODN insertion sites

  • The number of clusters.

Table 4
Clusters
library Alignments.x UMIs Insertions total both PCRs both Strands crRNA matched multiple Cuts In Oncogene Alignments.y
VEGFA_s1_K562_neg 1,651,287 479,108 94,975 91,503 7 487 1,524 185 104 link
VEGFA_s1_K562_pos 899,724 219,692 35,130 33,585 8 120 543 78 40 link

Cut sites were identified from the alignment start position of R2 reads.

  • Reads were aggregated if they share the exact same start position and the same UMI sequence.

  • UMI were corrected using the Adjacency method with a Hamming distance tolerance of 1.

  • Positions/UMI with more than 0 reads were considered for next step.

Clusters are defined as a group of ODN insertion sites within a distance smaller than 100 bp and characterized by :

  • Presence of reads aligning in both directions, indicating both ODN orientations (dual Orientation in table below)

  • Presence of multiple insertion sites positions (multiple Cuts in table below)

  • Match of the crRNA sequence with less than 6 edits withing the cluster boundaries +/- 50 bp (crRNA matched in table below)

Clusters with more than 0 total UMIs were considered.

Number of clusters per chromosome

This figure represents the distribution of unique clusters per chromosome, colored by the detection of the gRNA sequence with number of edits (INDELs and substitutions) smaller or equal to 6.

Number of UMI per chromosome

This figure represents the total number of UMIs (cells) per chromosome, colored by the detection of the gRNA sequence with number of edits (INDELs and substitutions) smaller or equal to 6.

This figure represents the total number of UMIs (cells) per chromosome, for clusters with gRNA match and colored by prediction status.

Rank-abundance curve

The rank-abundance curve is used in ecology to visualize species diversity in a community by plotting species abundance against species rank on logarithmic scales. The resulting curves shape provides insights into relative species abundance patterns and community evenness - a steep curve indicates dominance by a few species, while a shallow curve suggests more even distribution of abundances across species.

Only clusters with gRNA match and more than 1 total UMIs are plotted. Red dots correspond to clusters with 0 Edits in both crRNA and PAM sequences. Top3 most abundant clusters (UMI counts) are labeled.

################################################


################################################
## Off targets calling
tolerate_bulges: "TRUE"           # whether to include gaps in the gRNA alignment (this will change the gap penalty during SW pairwise alignment)
max_edits_crRNA: 6              # filter clusters with less or equal than n edits in the crRNA sequence (edits = substitutions + INDELs)
ISbinWindow: 100                # insertion sites closer than 'ISbinWindow' will be clustered together
minReadsPerUMI: 0               # 0 to keep all UMIs, otherwise min number of reads per UMIs
minUMIPerIS: 0                  # 0 to keep all IS, otherwise min number of UMI per IS
slopSize: 50                    # window size (bp) around IS (both directions) to identify gRNA sequence (ie 50bp = -50bp to +50bp)
min_predicted_distance: 100     # distance between cut site and predicted cut site to consider as predicted
################################################

################################################
